description:
Total co2 emission of this graph. 

MECE groups should have the same total_co2_emissions, with the exception of primary_demand:

We exclude the energy coming from non-energetic use converters. As they
are left of the primary energy demand and therefore not subtracted when 
calculating the total_co2_emission of primary_demand

final_demand.primary_co2_emission == useful_demand.primary_co2_emission != primary_demand.primary_co2_emission

query:

  DIVIDE(
    SUM( V( G(final_demand_cbs); primary_co2_emission ) ),
    PRODUCT( AREA( co2_emission_1990 ), BILLIONS )
  ),
  -1
)

query:
PRODUCT (
  MAX(
     SUM(
        V(Q(hh_heaters);
          simult_we*
          electricity_input_conversion*
          typical_capacity_gross_in_mj_s*
          share_of_heating_demand_households_energetic),
        NEG(
          V(micro_chp_households_energetic;
            simult_we*
            1/1000*
            share_of_heating_demand_households_energetic)
          )
        )
       ,
     0
     )
     ,
    AREA(number_households)
    )
description:
This query gives the peak load delta due to heater technologies using electricity.

In theory the query needs to be written for all 4 time periods: we, wd, se, sd. And then take the max value.

The electricity production of micro_chp compensates electricity demand by the other heaters. Without micro_chp the query would be:

PRODUCT (
     SUM(
        V(Q(hh_heaters);
          simult_we*
          electricity_input_conversion*
          typical_capacity_gross_in_mj_s*
          share_of_heating_demand_households_energetic)
         )
     ,
    AREA(number_households)
    )


Micro CHP capacity is 1/1000 MWe. In theory this value needs to be: 
  typical_capacity_gross_in_mj_s*electricity_output_conversion/useable_heat_output_conversion
However typical_capacity_gross_in_mj_s does not change in time while the heat output does..therefore this gives an incorrect value in future years.

Max value is used to make sure the peak load is always positive.
